President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed October 2022 as National Breast Cancer Awareness Month in the United States. In his proclamation, he highlights the challenges faced by individuals and families affected by breast cancer and emphasizes the importance of early screening and access to care. President Biden discusses the progress made in cancer research and treatment, including immunotherapies and early detection methods. He also mentions initiatives such as the Cancer Moonshot program and ARPA-H, which aim to accelerate research and improve patient outcomes. President Biden emphasizes the need to ensure access to screenings and treatments, mentioning the Affordable Care Act and the expansion of Medicaid. He encourages Americans to raise awareness about breast cancer and to prioritize screenings, particularly after a significant number of screenings were missed during the pandemic. President Biden concludes by urging unity in the fight against cancer and calls for a collective effort to end the disease.